Ordinary Differential Equations


Yuji Saikai
ysaikai@unimelb.edu.au
School of Mathematics and Statistics
The University of Melbourne

Introduction

A system of ordinary differential equations (ODEs) \[\frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{y}(t) = \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t))\]

We want to find a function \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) that satisfies the system, which is difficult and often impossible.

The corresponding numerical solution is a table that contains \(\mathbf{y}\) value for each of different \(t\).

We use as a running example the predator–prey model, which is based on the Lotka-Volterra equations.

Predator–prey model

Used to describe the population dynamics of two species, the one as a predator and the other as a prey.

The model consists of a pair of ODEs: \[\begin{align} \frac{dy_1}{dt} &= ay_1 - by_1y_2\\ \frac{dy_2}{dt} &= gby_1y_2 - ey_2 \end{align}\] where

  • \(y_1\) : prey population
  • \(y_2\) : predator population
  • \(a\) : natural growth rate of prey in the absence of predation
  • \(b\) : death rate due to the predation
  • \(g\) : birth rate of predator due to the captured prey
  • \(e\) : natural death rate of predator.

The system is known to have periodic solutions, which do not allow simple expressions.

Easy to obtain an implicit equation of \(y_1\) and \(y_2\). \[\begin{alignat}{2} &&(ay_1-by_1y_2)dy_2 &= (gby_1y_2-ey_2)dy_1\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad &\int \frac{a-by_2}{y_2}dy_2 &= \int \frac{gby_1-e}{y_1}dy_1\\ &\Leftrightarrow\quad & c &= gby_1-e\log(y_1)+by_2-a\log(y_2) \end{alignat}\] where \(c\) is a constant.

With \(a=0.05\), \(b=0.0002\), \(g=0.8\), \(e=0.03\), and \(c=-0.3\), we have the following orbit in a phase space.

a <- 0.05
b <- 0.0002
g <- 0.8
e <- 0.03
c <- -0.3
y1 <- seq(0, 800, length=1000)
y2 <- seq(0, 830, length=1000)
out <- outer(y1, y2, function(y1,y2) g*b*y1 - e*log(y1) + b*y2 - a*log(y2) )
contour(y1, y2, out, levels=c, lwd=1.5, drawlabels=F,
        xlab=bquote("prey" ~ (y[1])), ylab=bquote("predator" ~ (y[2])))
from_x <- c(16.05, 400, 500)
from_y <- c(401, 48, 652.3)
to_x <- c(16, 401, 499)
to_y <- c(400, 48.1, 653)
y0 <- c(150, 804)
points(y0[1], y0[2], pch=4, lwd=1.5)
text(y0[1], y0[2]-50, expression(y[0]), pos=4)
arrows(from_x, from_y, to_x, to_y, length=.1)
title("Periodic orbit in the predator-prey model")

Numerical solutions

If we knew \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) on the right-hand side of the above ODEs, a solution would be a usual integral with respect to \(t\): \[\mathbf{y}(t) = \int \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t))dt .\] An initial value problem \[ \mathbf{y}(t_1) = \mathbf{y}(t_0) + \int_{t_0}^{t_1} \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t))dt , \]

Solving a differential equation is doing integration.

Remember whether it is analytical or numerical integration, when it is hard, we approximate the integrand by simple functions.

Why don’t we apply the same idea here — approximating an unknown function \(\mathbf{y}(t)\)?

Starting with given \(\mathbf{y}(t_0)\) for \(t=t_0\), we can sequentially compute/simulate \(\mathbf{y}(t_1), \mathbf{y}(t_2), \dots\) and build a solution table as follows.

\(t\) \(\mathbf{y}(t)\)
\(t_0\) \(\mathbf{y}(t_0)\)
\(t_1\) \(\mathbf{y}(t_0) + \int_{t_0}^{t_1} \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t))dt\)
\(t_2\) \(\mathbf{y}(t_1) + \int_{t_1}^{t_2} \mathbf{f}(\mathbf{y}(t))dt\)
\(\vdots\)

Euler’s method

Let’s try linear approximation because its derivative is a constant and easy to integrate.

Let \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)\) be an approximation to \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) for \(t>0\), and \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) = \mathbf{y}(0)\).

If \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)\) is linear, then \[ \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)) = \frac{d}{dt}\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t) \] is a constant. A natural choice is \[ \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t)) = \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0)) \] for all \(t\in[0,h]\), and we can easily compute \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0))\) using the knowledge of \(\mathbf{f}\) and \(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) = \mathbf{y}(0)\).

Thus, \[\begin{align} \hat{\mathbf{y}}(h) &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) + \int_0^h \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0))dt\\ &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(0) + h\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(0)) \end{align}\]

Euler’s method for numerically solving ODEs is to make the following repeated approximation until \(t=nh+h\): \[\begin{align} \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh+h) &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh) + \int_{nh}^{nh+h} \mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh))dt\\ &= \hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh) + h\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh)) \end{align}\] for \(n\in\{0,1,\dots\}\).

Let’s illustrate it using the predator–prey model. Each process starts at \(\mathbf{y}_0=(150, 804)\), which is a point on the orbit.

LV <- function(y) c(a*y[1] - b*y[1]*y[2], g*b*y[1]*y[2] - e*y[2])
euler <- function(f, y0, h, N) {
  # Solution y(t) stored in a matrix for t∈{0,h,2h,...Nh}
  Y <- matrix(nrow=N+1, ncol=length(y0))
  
  Y[1,] <- y0
  for (n in 1:N) {
    Y[n+1,] <- Y[n,] + h*f(Y[n,])
  }
  return(Y)
}
for (h in c(1, 0.1)) {
  N <- 880/h
  Y <- euler(LV, y0, h, N)
  plot(Y[,1], Y[,2], type="l", xlab=bquote("prey" ~ (y[1])), ylab=bquote("predator" ~ (y[2])))
  points(Y[1,1], Y[1,2], pch=4, lwd=1.5)
  text(Y[1,1]+10, Y[1,2], expression(y[0]), pos=1)
  arrows(Y[N+1,1], Y[N+1,2],
         Y[N+1,1]+LV(Y[N+1,])[1], Y[N+1,2]+LV(Y[N+1,])[2], length=.1)
  title(paste("Euler's method (h = ", h, ")", sep=""))
}

With smaller \(h\) produces smaller errors.

The errors are smaller at the bottom-left and larger at the top-right. Why?

Even with \(h=0.05\), there is noticeable outward divergence from the orbit.

We should not excessively rely on small \(h\).

Our task is to come up with better approximation of \(\mathbf{y}(t)\) to reduce errors without decreasing \(h\).

Remember that, when approximating \(\mathbf{y}(t)\), we make two decisions: linearity and its slope.

Keep the linearity because it allows us to eliminate the dependency of the integrand \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(t))\) on \(t\in[nh,nh+h]\).

So, we try to engineer better slopes than the naïve choice \(\mathbf{f}(\hat{\mathbf{y}}(nh))\).
